way from gender equity and toward environmental concerns threatened to do away with the social and economic gains of the garden boom. Male landholders joined forestry personnel in attempts to displace the gardens and capture women's labor for the irrigation of male-controlled tree crops.This carefully documented microhistory draws on field experience spanning more than two decades and the insights of disciplines ranging from critical human geography to development studies. Schroeder combines the "success story" of the market gardens with a cautionary tale about the aggressive pursuit of natural resource management objectives, however well intentioned. He shows that questions of power and social justice at the community level need to enter the debates of policymakers and specialists in environment and development planning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAgroforestryzGambiazAlkalikunda. 0aDivision of laborzGambiazAlkalikunda. 0aForest ecologyzGambiazAlkalikunda. 0aMandingo (African people)xAgriculture. 0aMandingo (African people)xSocial conditions. 0aPatriarchyzGambiazAlkalikunda. 0aSex rolexPolitical aspectszGambiazAlkalikunda. 0aWomen, MandingoxEconomic conditions. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Geography.2bisacsh  a1970s.  a1980s.  aacademic.  acommunity.  acrops.  acultural studies.  adrought.  aeconomics.  aeconomy.  aenvironmental.  aenvironmentalist.  afarmers.  afarming.  afemale farmers.  aforestry.  agambia.  agardening.  agender politics.  agender roles.  agender studies.  ageography.  ahuman development.  airrigation.  alandowners.  amicrohistory.  anatural disaster.  apolitical.  apolitics.  ascholarly.  asmall town.  asocial justice.  avillage.  awest africa.  awomens labor.  aworking women.  aworld history.